He says it causes a heavy sensation in the scrotum. On examination the testis is non-tender and some 5 cm diameter. Investigations confirms this is a tumour and a right orchidectomy is performed.  Histological examination reveals cells with a characteristic \u0027fried egg\u0027 appearance.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Choriocarcinoma","Embryonal carcinoma","Seminoma","Teratoma","Yolk sac tumour"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case describes a classic presentation of \u003Cstrong\u003Eseminoma\u003C/strong\u003E. The key diagnostic features are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECharacteristic \u0027fried egg\u0027 histological appearance due to clear cytoplasm and central nuclei\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHigh radiosensitivity\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPainless testicular mass with heavy sensation\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EYolk sac tumours\u003C/strong\u003E typically occur in children and show Schiller-Duval bodies on histology. \u003Cstrong\u003EChoriocarcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E is highly vascular and presents with early haematogenous spread. \u003Cstrong\u003ETeratoma\u003C/strong\u003E contains elements from all three germ layers and is typically resistant to radiation. \u003Cstrong\u003EEmbryonal carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E is an aggressive tumour that presents with pain and rapid growth.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Seminomas have a classic \u0027fried egg\u0027 histological appearance and are highly radiosensitive.","Testicular seminomas typically present with painless testicular masses and a heavy sensation in the scrotum."],"references":["Boccellino M, Vanacore D, Zappavigna S, Cavaliere C, Rossetti S, D\u0027Aniello C, Chieffi P, Amler E, Buonerba C, Di Lorenzo G, Di Franco R, Izzo A, Piscitelli R, Iovane G, Muto P, Botti G, Perdon\u00e0 S, Caraglia M, Facchini G. Testicular cancer from diagnosis to epigenetic factors. Oncotarget. 2017 Sep 18;8(61):104654-104663. doi: 10.18632/oncotarget.20992. PMID: 29262668; PMCID: PMC5732834","Chung P, Warde P. Testicular cancer: germ cell tumours. BMJ Clin Evid. 2016 Jan 7;2016:1807. PMID: 26741128; PMCID: PMC4704678","Cheng L, Albers P, Berney DM, Feldman DR, Daugaard G, Gilligan T, Looijenga LHJ. Testicular cancer. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2018 Oct 5;4(1):29. doi: 10.1038/s41572-018-0029-0. PMID: 30291251","Ansell, I. D. (2012). Atlas of male reproductive pathology (Vol. 10). Springer Science \u0026 Business Media","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50129"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15876"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50129","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50129"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-24T16:01:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-24T16:02:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8567"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64695"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"t